  "prompt": "What are the comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of comparative legal approaches to money laundering across different nations:\n\n1. United States\n- Comprehensive Bank Secrecy Act and Anti-Money Laundering (AML) regulations\n- Strict reporting requirements for financial institutions\n- Aggressive criminal prosecution\n- Significant financial penalties for non-compliance\n\n2. European Union\n- Unified Anti-Money Laundering Directives\n- Consistent regulatory framework across member states\n- Enhanced customer due diligence requirements\n- Strong emphasis on financial transparency\n\n3. United Kingdom\n- Sophisticated financial intelligence unit\n- Risk-based regulatory approach\n- Extensive international cooperation\n- Strict corporate liability provisions\n\n4. Switzerland\n- Historically more lenient banking secrecy laws\n- Gradually increasing regulatory transparency\n- Strong international compliance standards\n- Sophisticated financial monitoring mechanisms\n\n5. China\n- Centralized regulatory approach\n- Strict criminal penalties\n- Growing emphasis on international cooperation\n- State-controlled financial monitoring\n\n6. Singapore\n- Robust regulatory framework\n- Advanced technological monitoring systems\n- Strict enforcement mechanisms\n- High penalties for non-compliance\n\n7. Brazil\n- Emerging regulatory environment\n- Increasing international collaboration\n- Developing comprehensive legal frameworks\n- Growing focus on financial crime prevention\n\nThese approaches reflect varying cultural, legal, and economic contexts.",
